    <p>CMOP-E, the Canadian Model of Occupational Performance and Engagement, provides OT students with a client-centred, occupation-focused framework for case studies, essays, and intervention planning assignments. Developed by Townsend, Polatajko, and the Canadian Association of Occupational Therapists (CAOT), the model evolved from the original CMOP (1997 Enabling Occupation) to CMOP-E (2007 Enabling Occupation II) with the addition of the Engagement dimension, recognising that occupational therapy addresses participation and meaning in occupation, not only task performance. CMOP-E organises the client's situation across three components, person, environment, and occupation, with spirituality at the centre of the person, and pairs directly with the Canadian Occupational Performance Measure (COPM) as its linked assessment tool and the Canadian Practice Process Framework (CPPF) as its linked process model. This service provides expert CMOP-E assignment help for BSc Year 2–3 and MSc OT students in the UK, Canada, and Australia.</p>

